         <editorialDecl>
            <normalization>
               <p>Manuscript abbrevations expanded, use of j/i and u/v modernized. No capitalization
                  or diacritics.</p>
            </normalization>
            <segmentation>
               <p>The text contains the following units: <list>
                     <item>Segments: A single phonological segment. Encoded by the "seg" element
                        with type=segment</item>
                     <item>Words: A syntactically independent sequence of Segments. Clitics are
                        treated as Words. Encoded using the "w" element.</item>
                     <item>Syllables: Sequence of Segments consisting minimally of a vocalic
                        nucleus. Since Words are syntactically rather than prosodically defined, a
                        Syllable can contain more than one word. Encoded by the "seg" element with
                        type=syllable</item>
                     <item>Lines: Sequence of both Words and Syllables forming a line of
                        verse.</item>
                  </list> The "join" attribute of w and pc elements encodes the manuscript word
                  division. </p>
            </segmentation>
            <punctuation>
               <p>Manuscript punctuation only, encoded in "pc" elements.</p>
            </punctuation>
            <correction>
               <p>Manuscript reading only modified where the text is uninterpretable and there is an
                  indisputable scriptological error (e.g. a repeated word or a missing initial).</p>
            </correction>
            <interpretation resp="#ogrsrc">
               <p>See <ref target="http://www.ogr-corpus.org">http://ogr-corpus.org</ref> for full
                  documentation of the annotation scheme.</p>
            </interpretation>
            <interpretation resp="#transcription">
                <p>The transcription and analysis is based on Berschin et al. (1981).
                The text is written in very small, faded characters in a single line.
                It was present on the parchment before a charter was copied in 1067.</p>
            </interpretation>
         </editorialDecl>
